Joint density plots, joint plots, and pairs plots in Seaborn¶

Import modules¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

import seaborn as sns

In [2]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
In [3]:
iris = sm.datasets.get_rdataset('iris').data

Joint distribution¶

We can create a scatter plot between two continuous variables in Seaborn.

In [5]:
sns.set_style('whitegrid')

sns.relplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='scatter', height=8)

plt.show()

We also know how to color or condition on a categorical variable via the hue semantic argument.

In [6]:
sns.relplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', hue='Species',
            kind='scatter', height=8)

plt.show()

2D histogram¶

In [7]:
sns.displot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='hist', height=8)

plt.show()

We can set the cbar argument to True to include the legend.

In [8]:
sns.displot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='hist', height=8,
            cbar=True)

plt.show()

Alternatively we can smooth out the counts and get an estimate for the density via a 2D kernel density estimate.

In [9]:
sns.displot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='kde', height=8)

plt.show()

Include the rug tick marks for additional context.

In [11]:
sns.displot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='kde', height=8,
            rug=True)

plt.show()

We can color the 2D kernel density estimate by a categorical therefore having the conditional kde.

In [12]:
sns.displot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', hue='Species',
            kind='kde', height=8)

plt.show()

Joint plots¶

Seaborn's terminology for combining a joint distribution with marginal distributions outside the main axis. Use 2D kde plot for the joint distribution and a 1D kde for the marginal distributions.

In [13]:
sns.jointplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='kde', height=8)

plt.show()

Instead we could use a scatter plot for the joint behavior and univariate histograms for the marginals. This is the default sns.jointplot() functionality.

In [14]:
sns.jointplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', height=8)

plt.show()

Alternatively we can use 2D histogram for the joint distribution.

In [15]:
sns.jointplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='hist', height=8)

plt.show()

Is sns.jointplot() includes hexbins to represent the joint distribution!

In [16]:
sns.jointplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='hex', height=8)

plt.show()

If we want to modify the marginal distribution settings we can change the keywords.

In [20]:
sns.jointplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', kind='hex', height=8,
              marginal_kws={'bins': 21})

plt.show()

We can color by a categorical variable as well.

In [21]:
sns.jointplot(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', hue='Species', kind='kde', height=8)

plt.show()

If we want additional control over the behavior of the plot, we can use the sns.JointGrid() function. For example, we can use boxplots for the marginals.

In [23]:
g = sns.JointGrid(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', height=8)
g.plot_joint(sns.histplot)
g.plot_marginals(sns.boxplot)

plt.show()

We can mix and match representing conditional and ungrouped behavior.

In [24]:
g = sns.JointGrid(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', hue='Species', height=8)
g.plot_joint(sns.histplot)
g.plot_marginals(sns.boxplot)

plt.show()
In [26]:
g = sns.JointGrid(data = iris, x='Sepal.Length', y='Sepal.Width', hue='Species', height=8)
g.plot_joint(sns.kdeplot)
g.plot_marginals(sns.boxplot)

plt.show()

Pairsplot¶

In Seaborn pairsplot only show the continuous variables.

In [27]:
sns.pairplot(iris)

plt.show()

We can color the markers and the marginal distributions by categorical variables.

In [28]:
sns.pairplot(data = iris, hue='Species')

plt.show()

If we want to control the lower, upper, and diagonal subplots we can use the sns.PairGrid() function.

In [29]:
g = sns.PairGrid(iris)

g.map_upper(sns.histplot)
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot)
g.map_diag(sns.histplot)

plt.show()

We can also color by and therefore condition on a categorical variable.

In [31]:
g = sns.PairGrid(iris, hue='Species')

g.map_upper(sns.histplot)
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot)
g.map_diag(sns.histplot, kde=True)

plt.show()
